WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.000
James Blair, Project Manager, Posit Workbench

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:13.000
Great. It's great to be with you all. I'm James Blair. I work at Posit as a product manager for cloud integrations.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:22.000
So today we're going to be talking about different ways that Posit Workbench can operate in different cloud environments through some of the partnerships that we're establishing today.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:29.000
Now, at Posit, we work really hard to make sure that Posit Workbench meets the needs of the modern data science developer.

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:35.000
This includes giving you tools and environments that allow you to do the day-to-day workloads that are important for your work.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:47.000
Exploratory data analysis, model training and tuning, deploying models, managing things of that nature, exploring data visually with tools like ggplot and other things like that, building shiny applications.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:55.000
Coding and working in other environments like VS Code and Jupyter Notebooks are all things that are supported under the Posit Workbench platform.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:08.000
Now, what's not often apparent to developers as they're working in this environment is the underlying infrastructure requirements that are sometimes complicated in order to support an enterprise product like Posit Workbench.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:18.000
To illustrate some of this complication, I want to take a moment to look at some of the documentation that we frequently share with customers when they're setting up Posit Workbench for the first time.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:20.000
It almost reads like a choose-your-own-adventure script.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:23.000
You can install Posit Workbench as its own environment.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:25.000
It can be a standalone server.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:30.000
This is typically the simplest approach, often the approach most people breeze right past.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:41.000
You can also choose to use Posit Workbench in a load balance environment where I have multiple nodes configured behind a load balancer and users are assigned different nodes based on different rules that might exist.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:47.000
This can be more robust, but obviously adds additional complication to the setup process.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:51.000
I could use Posit Workbench with an external resource manager like Kubernetes.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:53.000
Now I have Workbench set up.

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:55.000
I have a separate Kubernetes environment set up.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:57.000
Workbench communicates with that environment.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:01:59.000
Sessions launch in that environment.

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:01.000
This is a supported infrastructure.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:04.000
Or I could run the whole thing in Kubernetes.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:05.000
Workbench runs there.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:06.000
The sessions run there.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:07.000
Everything runs in Kubernetes.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:12.000
And then if I really want to make things interesting, I could also run and integrate with Slurm.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:18.000
Now, some people look at this, some internal IT organizations look at this documentation and this is how they feel.

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:21.000
They are salivating because they have the know-how.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:22.000
They have the expertise.

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:24.000
They have the infrastructure.

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:28.000
And it's almost a plug-and-play exercise to get Posit Workbench up and running.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:30.000
And we applaud those organizations.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:36.000
However, I also recognize that lots of people look at this and they feel more like this.

00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:38.000
I'm overworked.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:42.000
In many cases, I may be underpaid and I don't have time to figure out what Kubernetes is,

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:48.000
let alone figure out how to use it with this tool called Posit Workbench that if I'm in the IT organization,

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:51.000
I probably have very limited familiarity with.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:56.000
What we've noticed is that a lot of these administrators are starting to turn to the cloud to find solutions.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:02.000
They're looking for ready-made services or platforms that can alleviate some of this administrative burden

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:07.000
and supply users with the experience they want without creating an undue maintenance overload

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:11.000
for the IT professionals within the organization.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:14.000
Today, we're going to talk about a number of different solutions that exist today

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:19.000
and are coming in the near future that allow Posit Workbench and support Posit Workbench

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:21.000
inside of these different cloud environments.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:25.000
We'll talk about some of the advantages, how they differ from one another,

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:30.000
and provide some resources where you can learn more.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:33.000
We'll start with AWS or Amazon Web Services.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:37.000
We've partnered with Amazon SageMaker so that it's possible for administrators

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:43.000
to configure an Amazon SageMaker domain to have access to RStudio.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:46.000
In this process, an administrator goes in, they either create a new domain

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:50.000
or they go to an existing domain that exists in their SageMaker environment

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:53.000
and they make sure that there's a Posit license in place

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:58.000
and they can configure access to Posit Workbench and RStudio within that environment.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:02.000
Once that's been done, individual users can come into the SageMaker platform

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:06.000
and can request RStudio sessions from within that platform.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:10.000
When users make this request, they're brought to the familiar Posit Workbench homepage,

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:15.000
but there's a few key differences from what you might expect out of a traditional installation.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:20.000
One of the biggest things here is that users can request a specific compute instance type

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:22.000
for their session to run in.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:28.000
This means that every user gets an isolated EC2 instance within AWS for their particular session.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:31.000
This accomplishes two distinct things.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:36.000
One, users can request resources based on the workload they anticipate doing.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:40.000
If I have a huge data set and I plan on bringing it into memory and analyzing it,

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:41.000
I know I'm going to need a lot of memory.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:45.000
So, I can make a choice when I start my session to have an instance

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:48.000
that provides me with adequate memory for my analysis.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:52.000
On the other side, maybe I have an analysis that's going to require a lot of parallelization

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:54.000
across multiple CPU cores.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:58.000
To improve efficiency, I can request a compute instance that has a high CPU count

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:01.000
so that my workload finishes faster.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:06.000
The other advantage of this architecture is that everybody's sessions run independent of one another.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:08.000
This is hugely advantageous if you're like me

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:11.000
and you occasionally do something a little bit silly in RStudio

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:14.000
and all of a sudden the entire server is locked up.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:17.000
I'm sure I'm not the only one who's tried to read a data set into memory

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:21.000
that far exceeded the available memory in my environment.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:24.000
If that happens in a traditional single-server install,

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:26.000
I've now brought the server down for everyone.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:29.000
I had to buy more than one round of drinks to make up for that.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:35.000
Now, if you do the same thing here in the SageMaker environment,

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:39.000
you need to reset your session, but other users are unaffected.

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:43.000
If I do something in my session that causes me to exceed the available resources,

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:47.000
I'll need to start over and make sure that my new session contains adequate resources,

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:50.000
but I am not interrupting anyone else's workflow.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:54.000
The advantage here, and this is true for all of these solutions that we talk about,

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:58.000
is that this comes without additional IT administrative burden.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:01.000
The IT office does not need to worry about managing this environment.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:08.000
SageMaker handles the orchestration of the resources and everything behind the scenes.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:10.000
Let's talk about Google Cloud.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:15.000
We partnered with Google Cloud Workstations, which is a fairly new offering on GCP.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:18.000
This offering is kind of divided into two different personas.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:21.000
Administrators define workstation configurations

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:25.000
where they can define what resources are available for a given configuration

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:27.000
and what tools operate there,

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:31.000
and then users can come into the platform and request access to a given workstation.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:33.000
When a user makes this request,

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:36.000
a dedicated environment is created just for that user

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:40.000
that provides access to the tool set that was defined in the configuration

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:45.000
running on a specific instance that was also defined in that same configuration.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:49.000
When users come into the platform, they can see existing workstations they have,

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:53.000
they can request new workstations based on configurations they've been given access to,

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:56.000
and then they can launch workstations once they're running.

00:06:56.000 --> 00:06:58.000
And in the case of Posit Workbench,

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:01.000
they will then have access to all the tooling that they would expect to have access to

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:03.000
inside of a Workbench environment.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:09.000
VSCode, VRStudio IDE, Jupyter Notebooks, JupyterLab are all available within this integration.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:14.000
All IT has to do is configure these configurations to define what tools are available.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:19.000
Posit Workbench is available from a drop-down list of tools you might want to make available,

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:25.000
and then users can access it in their own dedicated compute environments.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:26.000
Next up is Databricks.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:28.000
This is one that we're very excited about.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:29.000
This is fairly new.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:31.000
We've published a few blog posts.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:34.000
In fact, one was published just last week that highlights some of this.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:36.000
And there's a number of things that are happening here,

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:38.000
so I'll spend a little bit more time here with Databricks.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:43.000
One is we've made a lot of progress recently on improving the SparklyR R package

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:47.000
to support some new and exciting developments on the Databricks side.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:52.000
Specifically, we're now able to take advantage of Databricks Connect from within SparklyR.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:57.000
What that means is I can remotely connect into a Databricks session and environment from anywhere.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:00.000
I don't have to be co-located, I don't have to use a Databricks notebook,

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:05.000
but I can have RStudio on my desktop, I can have Posit Workbench in AWS,

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:08.000
I can have an R terminal in some dusty server in a closet.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:09.000
It doesn't matter.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:13.000
I can use SparklyR to connect to Databricks

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:16.000
and facilitate workloads that happen in the Databricks environment.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:18.000
When I create these connections,

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:21.000
the connections pane in the upper right-hand corner of the RStudio IDE

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:25.000
will show me details about the data, the catalogs, the schemas,

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:28.000
everything that's available to me from that Databricks context.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:31.000
I can explore that data, I can connect to it, I can manipulate it,

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:35.000
and all of the computation happens on the Databricks end.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:39.000
We're also excited because we're creating a new feature inside the RStudio IDE

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:43.000
that's part of Posit Workbench that will allow Databricks users

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:46.000
to manage their clusters directly from the IDE.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:49.000
This means that if I'm using Databricks and I have a cluster that I want to connect to,

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:53.000
but it's not started yet, I don't have to open a browser, log into Databricks,

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:56.000
visit the control plane, click on Start Cluster, come back to the IDE,

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:59.000
wait for the cluster to start, connect to the cluster, and then work,

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:01.000
I can start the cluster directly from RStudio.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:04.000
Once it's started, I can connect directly to it and begin working.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:10.000
And this will be available in an upcoming release of Posit Workbench.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:12.000
The last thing that we're excited about, and this is more forward-looking,

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:14.000
this is not something that's available yet,

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:16.000
but we anticipate being available next year,

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:19.000
is Posit Workbench as a Lakehouse application.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:21.000
Databricks back in June announced Lakehouse applications

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:27.000
as a way to run third-party applications natively directly on Databricks infrastructure.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:30.000
What this means is that coming soon, like I mentioned sometime next year,

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:36.000
you'll be able to run Posit Workbench directly on your Databricks infrastructure

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:43.000
in a way that's supported, stable, and provides users with the experience they expect.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:44.000
I'll mention Snowflake briefly.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:47.000
This is one that we are in the very early stages with,

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:50.000
but we're working closely with Snowflake engineers and developers

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:54.000
to make it possible to run Posit Workbench as part of Snowpark Container Services,

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:59.000
which is a fairly recently announced new development over at Snowflake.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:01.000
The idea is that you'll be able to run Posit Workbench

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:05.000
directly within your Snowflake environment.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:09.000
And when you do that, you'll also have access to the same connections pane

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:12.000
that we looked at previously that will allow you to explore the data

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:15.000
that's available to you within Snowflake, run queries against that data,

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:18.000
use that data for analysis, all while staying within the realm

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:21.000
of your Snowflake architecture and infrastructure.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:24.000
This is still really early phases, so more documentation and more examples

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:30.000
will be available soon as we continue to work through this integration.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:32.000
Finally, last but not least, we have Posit Cloud.

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:35.000
We've done a lot recently to make Posit Cloud more robust,

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:39.000
more capable, and more feature-rich as we've listened to feedback from our users.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:43.000
This is a really great kind of low-barrier way to get exposure

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:47.000
to some of the products and features that we offer to enterprise customers.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:49.000
Anyone can create an account on Posit Cloud.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:51.000
And from that account, you can create workspaces,

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:55.000
you can create projects that are leveraging either the RStudio IDE

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:56.000
or Jupyter Notebooks.

00:10:56.000 --> 00:11:00.000
And from those projects, you can then publish things to Posit Cloud

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:02.000
and share and distribute those with others.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:10.000
And we continue to build out this platform to improve the user experience.

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:13.000
As we look towards the future, it's clear that the cloud landscape

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:14.000
is always shifting.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:16.000
There's new technologies that arrive.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:18.000
There's technologies that disappear.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:21.000
But here at Posit, we remain committed to making sure that regardless

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:26.000
of where your organization chooses to operate, we are a natural fit,

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:28.000
that our products work well in those environments,

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:32.000
and that in many cases, we find ways to make sure that they not only work well,

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:34.000
but that they work in a way that doesn't add additional burden

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:38.000
to IT organizations that are often already overworked.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:41.000
We look forward to a future where all of Posit team,

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:45.000
not just Posit Workbench, but Posit Connect, Posit Package Manager,

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:47.000
are available in these different cloud environments,

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:49.000
and it's something that we are diligently working towards

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:52.000
with all these different partnerships.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:54.000
So what's next?

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:58.000
If you attended today and didn't see your cloud provider

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:01.000
or cloud service of choice in what we've talked about,

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:02.000
feel free to reach out to me.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:04.000
You can find me at james.posit.co.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:07.000
I'd love to chat or set up a discussion about things that you are doing

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:09.000
within your organization or tools that you're using

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:13.000
that you would like to see work better with Posit tools and Posit products.

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:17.000
Alternatively, if you are a user of one of these services,

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:21.000
you use Snowflake, you use Databricks, you're operating in GCP or AWS,

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:23.000
whatever the case is, if you have questions

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:26.000
or if you have feedback on the existing integrations,

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:30.000
again, happy to receive that and happy to have you reach out.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:31.000
Here's a collection of resources.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:34.000
These are links that will take you to different blog posts,

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:37.000
documentation things that outline some of the work that's happening right now,

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:40.000
places that you can keep an eye on for the future.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:43.000
This is all available if you scan the QR code here.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:46.000
This will take you to a GitHub repository that contains the slides,

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:49.000
links to everything that I've just shared, and things like that.

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:51.000
But I appreciate your time today.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:53.000
Thank you very much, and we'll take some questions.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:13:00.000
Thank you, James.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:03.000
So I have some questions here, actually.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:07.000
How does Posit choose which provider or features to prioritize,

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:10.000
and is there any possibility of a technical roadmap?

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:12.000
Yeah, this is such a good question.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:17.000
It's like, it's more of like an art than a science, right?

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:23.000
So what I mean by that is each of these partnerships that we have is kind of this,

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:25.000
you know, there's two sides to it, right?

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:30.000
We obviously want to make sure that our products are as well represented

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:33.000
and as well positioned as they can be in each of these different environments.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:37.000
But we're also balancing that against the needs, demands,

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:40.000
expectations of the group or company that we're working with.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:43.000
And so a lot of it just comes down to the requirements that they might have

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:47.000
or the expectations they might have and where we end up meeting in the middle.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:49.000
An example of this would be SageMaker, right?

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:51.000
SageMaker has SageMaker Studio,

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:55.000
which is a JupyterLab-based interface for interacting with their platform.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:59.000
So when we came to them and when we started these discussions about Posit Workbench,

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:03.000
one of the things that they didn't want to do was they didn't want to enable

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:06.000
Jupyter Notebooks and JupyterLab and VS Code within Workbench

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:10.000
because they wanted Python users to continue to rely on the solution they provide.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:13.000
And so if you use SageMaker and Posit Workbench today,

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:17.000
you'll notice that the only editor that's available in that context is the RStudio editor

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:21.000
because of some of the tradeoffs we made in our conversations with Amazon.

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:26.000
So one of the things that I focus on and think about a lot is how I can make sure

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:29.000
that our product integrations are as consistent as they can be

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:33.000
across the different partners that we partner with,

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:36.000
but also while acknowledging that in some cases there's expectations

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:38.000
and things that need to be taken into consideration

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:42.000
that might make the experience a little bit different from one to the other.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:44.000
Thank you.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:49.000
Is only providing RStudio or SageMaker an AWS limitation?

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:52.000
Would you be able to run VS Code in the near future?

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:55.000
Yes. See previous response.

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:59.000
Yeah, so we've talked to them a lot about that, right?

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:04.000
I'd love it if they opened up some additional functionality on the SageMaker side.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:09.000
In all honesty, I don't expect that that will change anytime in the near future.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:15.000
But the one thing that I'll say, and this is true of any of these types of questions,

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:19.000
is that if you have questions like this around how come this isn't this way

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:22.000
or why is it this way, let us know about it.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:24.000
Also, if you have a relationship with SageMaker,

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:28.000
if you're a SageMaker customer or an Amazon customer or with Databricks or whatever,

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:31.000
reach out to your reps on their end as well and provide that feedback for them.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:34.000
Because they're managing their own roadmaps

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:37.000
and we're trying to kind of jointly work on that with them.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:39.000
But these providers getting that feedback directly

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:43.000
is often the thing that will help move things forward the best.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:44.000
Thank you.

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:47.000
So I work in a highly regulated industry.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:52.000
Do any of these cloud service providers or provide encryption in transit,

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:56.000
at rest, and even during use?

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:58.000
Yeah, that's a really good question.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:02.000
I know SageMaker has several different compliance requirements that it meets.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:04.000
I know it's SOC 2 compliant, there's HIPAA compliance,

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:07.000
there's some other things that are there on the SageMaker side.

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:13.000
It really depends, and that's a good question for the provider or the partner.

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:16.000
One of the things that I don't have a clear answer for right now

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:20.000
is as we look towards the future with Databricks and the work that we're doing there,

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:24.000
being able to operate directly on Databricks infrastructure,

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:28.000
which means that data wouldn't ever travel outside of your Databricks environment.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:30.000
Workbench would be there.

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:33.000
As you analyze data, it would stay within the realm of Databricks.

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:36.000
There might be some things there that meet some regulatory requirements,

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:39.000
but that would be a question better suited for Databricks in that case.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:40.000
Thanks.

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:45.000
So the next question reads,

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:50.000
can these solutions connect to Package Manager and have the workbench environments

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:55.000
use only packages available based on freeze dates?

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:57.000
What was the last part? Available on?

00:16:57.000 --> 00:16:59.000
On freeze dates, like frozen freeze dates.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:02.000
Oh, freeze, gotcha. Yeah.

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:06.000
So yes is the short answer, right?

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:09.000
It depends on which particular integration or partnership we're talking about.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:13.000
For example, SageMaker lets you configure at the domain level

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:16.000
when you set up a SageMaker domain and configure our studio,

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:20.000
you can supply a default package repository URL.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:24.000
And so if you have like a snapshot from Package Manager that you want every user to use,

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:28.000
you can supply it there and then every user session will by default point to that location.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:31.000
And other solutions like the GCP solution

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:34.000
or the stuff that we're doing with Snowflake and things like that,

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:37.000
everything is a little bit further down the line

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:41.000
where you're managing containers and image definitions

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:44.000
to provide users with access to the tooling.

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:50.000
And so things can be implemented at that level to set defaults for upstream repositories or things like that.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:52.000
Thank you again. Appreciate it, James.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:54.000
Thank you.

